# Fake News Detection using Multinomial Naive Bayes

## Project Overview

This Machine Learning and Natural Language Processing (NLP) project classifies news articles as FAKE or TRUE using text analysis.

The project uses CountVectorizer to convert text into numerical features and Multinomial Naive Bayes to classify news articles based on word frequencies.

The model achieved an accuracy of 95.28%, demonstrating the effectiveness of Naive Bayes for text classification tasks.

---

## Business Problem

Fake news spreads misinformation and can influence public opinion, decision-making, and social trust.

The goal of this project is to automatically identify whether a news article is:

* FAKE
* TRUE

using machine learning and natural language processing techniques.

---

## Dataset Information

### Dataset

Fake and Real News Dataset

### Total Records

44,898 News Articles

### Features

* title
* text
* subject
* date

### Target Variable

```text
label
```

Classes:

```text
FAKE
TRUE
```

### Class Distribution

```text
FAKE = 23,481
TRUE = 21,417
```

The dataset is well balanced, making it suitable for classification tasks.

---

## Data Preprocessing

### Missing Values

No missing values were found.

### Feature Engineering

The title and article text were combined into a single feature:

```python
df["content"] = df["title"] + " " + df["text"]
```

This allows the model to learn from both headlines and article content.

### Removed Columns

* date

Reason:

The project focuses on text classification and publication dates were not required for prediction.

---

## Text Vectorization

### CountVectorizer

Machine learning models cannot understand raw text.

CountVectorizer converts words into numerical features.

Example:

Article:

```text
cat dog
```

becomes:

| cat | dog | fish |
| --- | --- | ---- |
| 1   | 1   | 0    |

After vectorization:

```text
44,898 Articles
122,513 Unique Words
```

Shape:

```text
(44898, 122513)
```

---

## Machine Learning Workflow

1. Load Dataset
2. Create Target Labels
3. Merge Fake and True News Datasets
4. Shuffle Dataset
5. Text Preprocessing
6. CountVectorizer
7. Train-Test Split
8. Train Multinomial Naive Bayes
9. Generate Predictions
10. Evaluate Performance

---

## Model Used

### Multinomial Naive Bayes

Multinomial Naive Bayes is one of the most effective algorithms for text classification because it works with word frequency data.

Reasons for choosing MultinomialNB:

* Fast Training
* Excellent for NLP Tasks
* Handles High-Dimensional Data
* Works Well with CountVectorizer Features

---

## Model Performance

### Accuracy

```text
95.28%
```

### Confusion Matrix

```text
[[4479  231]
 [ 193 4077]]
```

### Classification Report

| Class | Precision | Recall | F1 Score |
| ----- | --------- | ------ | -------- |
| FAKE  | 0.96      | 0.95   | 0.95     |
| TRUE  | 0.95      | 0.95   | 0.95     |

---

## Results Interpretation

The model correctly classifies the vast majority of news articles.

### FAKE News

Correctly Identified:

```text
4479 / 4710
```

### TRUE News

Correctly Identified:

```text
4077 / 4270
```

The model achieved balanced performance across both classes, with strong precision and recall scores.

---

## User Prediction Example

```python
news = input("Enter a news article: ")

news_vector = vectorizer.transform([news])

prediction = model.predict(news_vector)

print("Prediction:", prediction[0])
```

Example Output:

```text
Prediction: FAKE
```

or

```text
Prediction: TRUE
```

